The '''Tasmanian boobook''' ('''''Ninox leucopsis'''''), also known as the '''Tasmanian spotted owl''', is a species of [[owl]] in the family [[Strigidae]]. It is native to [[Tasmania]].

Formerly considered conspecific with the [[morepork]] (''N. novaeseelandiae''), phylogenetic studies have affirmed its status as a distinct species by analyzing genetic and morphologic characteristics.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Gwee |first1=Chyi Yin |last2=Christidis |first2=Les |last3=Eaton |first3=James A. |last4=Norman |first4=Janette A. |last5=Trainor |first5=Colin R. |last6=Verbelen |first6=Philippe |last7=Rheindt |first7=Frank E. |date=2017 |title=Bioacoustic and multi-locus DNA data of Ninox owls support high incidence of extinction and recolonisation on small, low-lying islands across Wallacea |journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution |volume=109 |pages=246–258 |doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2016.12.024 |pmid=28017857 |bibcode=2017MolPE.109..246G |issn=1055-7903}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Michael Wink |title=Owls of the World |author2=Petra Heidrich |author3=Hedi Sauer-Gürth |author4=Abdel-Aziz Elsayed |author5=Javier Gonzalez |date=2008 |publisher=A&C Black |isbn=978-1-4081-0884-0 |editor1=König, Claus |edition=2nd |pages=42–63 |chapter=Molecular phylogeny and systematics of owls (Strigiformes) |editor2=Weick, Friedhelm |name-list-style=amp}}</ref> It was reclassified as distinct by the [[International Ornithologists' Union|International Ornithological Congress]] in 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Owls – IOC World Bird List |url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/new/bow/owls/ |access-date=2022-08-24 |language=en-US}}</ref>

It is widespread in Tasmania and on [[King Island (Tasmania)|King Island]] and other islands of Bass Strait.{{sfn|Higgins|1999|p=855}} It has been recorded in southern Victoria, once from New South Wales,{{sfn|Higgins|1999|p=872}} and once from [[Lord Howe Island]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Tsang |first1=Leah |last2=Carlile |first2=Nicholas |last3=O'Dwyer |first3=Terry |last4=Eldridge |first4=Mark |last5=Frankham |first5=Greta |last6=Bower |first6=Hank |date=2022 |title=A recent specimen of a Tasmanian Boobook Ninox leucopsis recovered on Lord Howe Island |journal=Australian Field Ornithology |volume=39 |pages=143–157 |url=https://afo.birdlife.org.au/afo/index.php/afo/article/view/2265 |doi=10.20938/afo39143157 |doi-access=free|url-access=subscription }}</ref> It predominantly occurs in [[eucalypt]] forests.{{sfn|Higgins|1999|p=854}}

It is [[Carnivore|carnivorous]], and a nest [[Predation|predator]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Barwood |first1=Donna |last2=Smith |first2=Sandra |last3=Miller |first3=Margaret |last4=Boston |first4=Julie |last5=Masek |first5=Martin |last6=Devine |first6=Amanda |date=April 2020 |title=Transformational Game Trial in Nutrition Education |journal=Australian Journal of Teacher Education |volume=45 |issue=4 |pages=18–29 |doi=10.14221/ajte.2020v45n4.2 |issn=1835-517X|doi-access=free }}</ref>

The Tasmanian boobook is [[Sexual dimorphism|sexually dimorphic]], with males typically being smaller than females.{{sfn|Tsang|Carlile|O'Dwyer|Eldridge|2022}}

